<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900920-0036</DOCNO><DOCID>900920-0036.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>09/20/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   THE ECONOMY is moving closer to a recession as a result ofthe jump in oil prices, Fed Chairman Greenspan told Congress.He said the central bank's ability to resist a recession bylowering interest rates has been frustrated by inflationarypres sures. However, he didn't rule out a long-anticipatedmove to lower rates.                                                                                                       </LP><TEXT>   A Fed survey shows that the Mideast crisis already israising manufacturers' costs, damping consumer buying andcausing widespread uncertainty in the business community.   ---   Northwest Airlines received a $500 million cash infusionfrom Airbus Industrie and General Electric. The Europeanconsortium arranged the low-interest loan after Northwestagreed to buy 75 more Airbus planes and take options on 30others. A GE team will supply the engines for the aircraft.   ---   Pan Am plans to slash 2,500 jobs, eliminate sometrans-Atlantic service and shift to smaller planes to combathigher fuel costs and light traffic.   ---   Northrop's chairman retired just as an InternationalChamber of Commerce ruling surfaced saying that $6.2 millionin payments by the firm to South Korea were meant to induceSeoul to buy Northrop fighter planes.   ---   The Reichmann family is trying to sell a nearly 20%partnership interest in its U.S. real estate portfolio.Industry officials said the stake could fetch as much as $800million.   ---   The FCC approved broad changes in the way it regulatesfees long-distance carriers pay for access to local phonenetworks. It projected billions of dollars in savings forconsumers, but some user groups were skeptical.   ---   American General said it may settle for selling only itshome-service life insurance business, claiming it's havingtrouble finding a buyer for the entire financial-servicesconcern.   ---   The Sandamp;L bailout agency told a House panel that it willneed about $122 billion in funding for the fiscal yearstarting Oct. 1, more than double what was anticipated a yearago.   ---   Donald Trump wants to restructure $245 million in debtpayments still due on loans made for the Trump Shuttle. Mr.Trump cited soaring fuel costs and a soft Northeast economy.   ---   Small investors seeking punitive damages in arbitrationdisputes with brokers suffered a setback when a judge ruledpunitive damages can't always be awarded in such cases.   ---   First Executive's claims that unreleased reports prove itslong-term financial viability appear to fall far short ofthat assertion.   ---   The budget standoff isn't giving a political advantage tothe Republicans or the Democrats, a Wall Street Journal/NBCNews poll found.   ---   The life insurance industry is likely to see its federaltax bill jump by $2 billion a year, partly because stock andmutual insurance companies haven't resolved a tax squabble.   ---   Time Warner will consolidate its publishing operationsinto a new unit that will include its magazine business andbook publishing operation.   ---   The GAO is concerned bank regulators are making some ofthe same mistakes that led to the Sandamp;L crisis.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 147,530,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2557.43, off 13.86; transportation 888.31, off 13.13;utilities 201.52, up 1.00.   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Brothers Treasury index 3345.45, up16.30.   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 131.66, off 0.62;spot index 128.90, off 0.53.   Dollar: 137.52 yen, off 0.33; 1.5715 marks, up 0.0185.</TEXT></DOC>